While I do tend to shift some details of dialogue around, I'm an edit up kind of writer. Doesn't mean I haven't cut big at times. But if I do, I usually rewrite a scene wholesale because the conversation doesn't serve the purpose.

What I usually advise - read it out loud and correct obvious flaws. If your tongue trips, it's not clean. Then look at your pacing. Are your paragraphs (lines if just doing greentext) clear and have a definite chunk of info? Are you repeating previous info that the reader shouldn't need reminding of? Do we have dangling info that is never resolved?
Think visually as well as audibly. One of the things I'm editing has the two characters with difference outfits. Sensory wise, I need to allow those sounds and sights to occur. Where I've already set up the movements for them, maybe I can trim. Just leaves more space to burrow inside the two character's thoughts

Anonymous Mon 14 Dec 2020 03:20:22 No.34733806 Report

>>34733238
Well, I can give you some hints from a someone writing a book #2

Learn what you can about your scenes and set pieces in the first drafts. I'll assume you have a rough outline and those are just the parts that you know the most about.
I'd then advise you to look at whether you are naturally a more character based writer, or plot based. Once you're there, pacing (that mental camera) seems less of a hurdle. I'm pretty even myself, but any one chunk of a story could veer in either direction. Sure, I'll ramble in my first draft. That isn't the final draft.
A useful exercise is to do some character questionnaires. If you can think as the character, you'll write more naturally. Let them ramble, then step back and consider the statue you're hewing out of the marble block.

Just do whatever part of the dialogue/narration/exposition comes first. Fill in the blanks later. Trust the story in your head. The best artists think through the tool. You don't think of how to write the letters onto the page. A sculptor knows intuitively how to hold the chisel. A musician has no gap between the notes and will.
All that exists is your fear and anxiety. They are part of the process.
Be, with all of your doubting, motherfucking heart!
Near impossible is not impossible. You started. She waits for you to chisel her free.
